entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued February 11 at 5:07AM AKST by NWS Fairbanks AK
entry.summary:
A strong low pressure system will move into Bristol Bay during the day on Monday. This system will bring a large amount of warm and moist air over Western Alaska starting Monday into Tuesday. There is still a good deal of uncertainty on the strength and track of the system, but areas from Unalakleet south have a chance of freezing rain beginning Monday afternoon, with a chance of freezing rain spreading north to Kotzebue by Tuesday afternoon. Significant ice accumulations are possible and will be monitored as the event gets closer and details become more clear.
This storm could also bring heavy snow to the east side of the Nulato Hills, the the Southern Seward Peninsula, and to areas north of the Kobuk River. There could be brief blizzard conditions along the West Coast as well.
The system will also bring strong southeast winds gusting as high as 50 mph to the West Coast and to hills near the coast from Monday afternoon through Tuesday night. This will cause sea levels to rise 1 to 2 feet south of the Bering Strait on Tuesday and Wednesday. While flooding of infrastructure is not expected, these strong winds may cause water to be pushed on top of the sea ice making travel difficult.
Residents should stay tuned to the latest forecast updates at www.weather.gov/afg and prepare for a stormy start to the week.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued February 10 at 4:15PM AKST by NWS Fairbanks AK
entry.summary:
A strong low pressure system will move into Bristol Bay during the day on Monday. This system will bring a large amount of warm and moist air over Western Alaska starting Monday into Tuesday. There is still a good deal of uncertainty on the strength and track of the system, but areas from Unalakleet south have a chance of freezing rain beginning Monday afternoon, with a chance of freezing rain spreading north to Kotzebue by Tuesday afternoon. Significant ice accumulations are possible and will be monitored as the event gets closer and details become more clear.
This storm could also bring heavy snow to the east side of the Nulato Hills, the the Southern Seward Peninsula, and to areas north of the Kobuk River. There could be brief blizzard conditions along the West Coast as well.
The system will also bring strong southeast winds gusting as high as 50 mph to the West Coast and to hills near the coast from Monday afternoon through Tuesday night. This will cause sea levels to rise several feet south of the Bering Strait on Tuesday and Wednesday. While flooding of infrastructure is not expected, these strong winds may cause water to be pushed on top of the sea ice making travel difficult.
Residents should stay tuned to the latest forecast updates at www.weather.gov/afg and prepare for a stormy start to the week.
